description:
Meteorites are Max Turner and Marcus Rossknecht. Both are known for their involvement in the underground pop and experimental music scenes of the last decade, both having a substantial roster of releases and production credits to their name. This collaborative project is different from both their solo ventures and combines a multitude of sonic affinities reaching from nerdy R´n´B to island riddims and spoken word poetry. As the Ep’s videosingle “Blood & Stardust” suggest, the sounds are borderline sci-fi and strangely esoteric, with caribbean edge and quality modular synths bubbling up between thick bass lines, jumpy mute guitars and cosmic choirs. 

Max Turner resumes his work as vocalist after a sabbatical period of 5 years in India where he encountered the musical spice that seems to drive this sweetly scented catalog and joins the loosely flavoured rap he has come to be known for with more elaborate melody. He is the co-founder of Puppetmastaz, and is also known for a wide scope of collaborative releases and solo material such as “Infinite 4x4” and “Oranges”. Discography: http://www.discogs.com/artist/19736-Max-Turner

Marcus Rossknecht is a producer and DJ from Berlin who has  been active in many musical contexts, from pursuing his own tracks or delivering remixes to producing for Andreas Dorau in his early days and on to sculpting Matias Aguayo´s most celebrated successes on records such as “Are you really lost” and “Ayayay”, both of which Rossknecht produced in his sonic laboratory single-handedly.´Groovescript´ is his brain child and label imprint, a record label and production company that promises a wild roster of future releases, “Transform the Waves” being the first. Discography: http://www.discogs.com/artist/586473-Marcus-Rossknecht

JEVNE

Owner and operator of Onethirty Recordings, from deep to teky from soulful to pumping, Jevne's sets are a journey through house music you will not want to miss. Check out his LUV2GLOW party in Key West FL during Fantasy Fest!
From 2005-2015 Jevne consistently traveled the world playing live bass guitar along with his Dj sets, his talents brought him to South America, Europe, Switzerland, Canada and all over the United States for gigs!

2014 marked 10 awesome years of Onethirty Recordings! Back in 2004 the label was launched by Jevne Miller as an outlet for his music and other artists Jevne respects. Onethirty swirls in deep house, tech-house and funky vibes, always flourishing and flowing with the current sounds of house music. Onethirty consistently released music by many of the most influential producers in dance music including: Justin Martin, Robert Owens, Hipp-E, Roberto Rodriguez, Chuck Love, Jay-J, Ian Pooley, Shur-i-Kan, Johnny Fiasco, Atnarko,  Leo & Ronan Portela, Scope and many more. Onethirty also had a hand in launching new artists that have gone on to make solid names in the house music world such as Raxon, Emil Lanne, Random Soul, Metodi Hristov, Onur Ozman, Edmund  & Javi Lopez.


Jevne's original production and remixes have appeared on many respected labels & compilations including: Shifted Music (Jay-J's label), Johnny Fiasco's Klassik Fiasco, Urban Torque, Soulman Music, Ospina Digital, Open Bar, Eighth Dimension, Conya, Coastline, Chillin, Kolour, Clubstar, Native Soul and more. His tracks have been remixed by the talents of Ian Pooley, Chuck Love, Tony Thomas, Fred Everything, Manuel Tur, Asad Rizvi & Justin Martin to name a few. Keep your eye & ears on Jevne & Onethirty Recordings!

Ananda grew up in an very musical family and played piano and drums., but never got the "click" to make active music. There was a band with a few friends but it was not very professional, just to have fun.

In October 2006 he met a musican from Ravensburg. From the moment of first talking with this guy (he is making music only with Hardware) Ananda's idea of self making music came back. He remembered that there is an ancient midi controller keyboard somewhere between the electronical stuff, got it out and tried a little bit around with vsts and so on. But he missed the "real" musical feeling. That was the step to Ananda's first synthi: the Roland SH-201. In the meanwhile there is a lot of more stuff and there will be more in future.

Paul Beynon, like most DJ/Producers, has always used music as an expression of his emotions and passion. Unlike countless others, Paul is a self taught musician, producer and artist, with the technical knowledge of music theory, he has combined it with his knowledge of production to create a wide array of unique music. After losing all of his original material in 2003, Paul Beynon didn’t produce anything until 2005, when he rediscovered his passion. It wasn't long until he'd set up a new studio and soon after that quit his day job to pursue studies in Sound Engineering. Paul was soon finishing tune after tune and it was not long before he collaborated with local DJ and producer Darius Bassiray for "Jeebuzz Champ" which was released on Dieb Audio. The pair decided to make a platform for their work and established the label Text Book Music. Text Book Music showcases a unique group of artists from Melbourne, Australia as well as benchmark producers from around the world. The aim of Text Book Music is simple – quality deep, multifaceted and profound house music that is dynamic and distinctive. Paul soon collaborated with Bassiray continuing their 'Balls Deep' remix series on Darius' "El Camino". He also released his original "Psychedelic Beach Doof" through Text Book Music; again balls deeping the original with Darius Bassiray. This release was praised by many tastemakers throughout the world including Terry Francis, D.Diggler, Richie Hawtin, Nils Nurnberg, John Selway, Chloe Harris, Slam, Deepchild, Chris Fortier, Erphun, Atmos, Taster Peter, and many more.

He was on the second place. He was even invited in some radio shows like Live mix @ ONE Fm, One Guest @ One FM, Next Level @ Radio 21 ,BPM @ MiniSat Targoviste, Dance Floor @ TribalMixes Radio and Sounds of Electro @ Delta FM, exclusive set's broadcasted at IbizaGlobalRadio. The London based Bad Boy DJs is the joint melting pot of creativity brought to you by Tim Rundle aka Funk Republic, and Steve Brock aka Brockenspiel.

Both experienced DJs in their own right, they smashed their way onto the House Music scene in 2007 when their debut track ‘House Music Will Never Die’ got the blessing of none other than Mr Pete Tong when he declared it his best unsigned track of the week, which led to it being snapped up by the mighty Chicago based label, Funktion Recordings.

Since that time, this energetic duo have quickly been gaining recognition from some of the industries leading players as well as attracting fans from far and wide, and since their incarnation they have been lucky enough to work with, and remix for, some of the industries top DJs and producers including names such as Jerry Ropero, Lissat & Voltaxx, Supermal, Chriss Ortega and The House Moguls, and have released music on labels including Emotive Sounds, Interlabel, Funktion Recordings, Bandito and Kingdom Kome Cuts.

2009 has already been a great year for the boys as they saw the release of their highly anticipated two track  ‘We’re Underground EP’ smash its way through the DJdownload charts peaking at number 3, as their unique style of glitchy tinged, wonky electro tech does the damage on dancefloors across the globe.

Michael Shoup has been working full time in the music industry since 2004.  He has been featured as a spotlight performer at highly coveted showcase slots at SXSW Music Festival in Austin, TX as well as the CMJ Music Marathon in New York City. Michael has toured with The Stone Temple Pilots and has worked with artists such as Lady Antebellum, Taylor Swift, Brad Paisley, and Kelly Clarkson. Michael's music is genuine and melodically timeless. He has even made an impression on Steven Schwartz (composer and lyricist of the musical, Wicked) who flew Shoup to his home in Los Angeles to perform a cover of "Defying Gravity."

“Personally, I like to think of my music as one part Jackson Browne, one part Hall & Oates, two big scoops of everything I heard from my stereo in the ’90s, and a sprinkling of Sesame Street optimism,” Shoup says of his songwriting.  Whether from his own life or taken directly from a fan suggestion, few artists' songs can connect directly with their fans as much as Michael Shoup's. After releasing his debut solo album, “Learning How To Live” in November of 2010, he's launched multiple songwriting campaigns which allow readers of his blog to submit ideas that may inspire a song including lyrics, photos, videos, stories and more. Michael's music is availalbe for download from his website, iTunes, and Amazon.

Since 1997 the name Playdoughboy is being synonymous with house music. Starting out as a producer, Playdoughboy has a reputation of a house music pioneer always pushing the limits and looking ahead. This ability to foresee the history of what’s hot put Playdoughboy on the map as one of the in demand DJs in San Francisco.

At this moment Playdoughboy has over a dozen of releases under his belt on some of the most influential labels including Freaks Culture Records, Mizumo Music, and KGBeats Records to name a few. His original tracks and bootleg remixes can be heard in sets of DJs all over the globe from Ibiza to Berlin. 

He performed live and as a DJ at the most prestigious clubs in San Francisco including Ruby Skye, 1015 Folsom, Slide, Mighty, Supperclub, Roe/Prive, Vessel, Temple. Playdoughboy shared the stage with Global Deejays (Austria), Bobina (Russia), Sasha Dith (Germany), Pheek (Canada), Mark Farina (USA), Lee Burridge (UK), Tom Middleton (UK), DJ Grad (Russia), Cybersutra (USA). Guest appearances include SpyBar (Chicago), Ibiza (Seattle), C89.5 FM (Seattle), Maska (Kharkov, Ukraine), El Otro Mundo Sessions on deepmix.FM, Loveparade SF 2004 and 2007, Folsom Street Fair 2006.

Playdoughboy’s collaborations include works with Aier Sauft, John Bourke, Protection, Fat Magic and Rachel Car. 2010 is the year the world will see another Playdoughboy’s project – Nuwax Records.

From 1997 to 2004, I composed primarily in ModPlug Tracker, with help from other audio applications as needed. As of late 2004, I moved to using Reason to better improve quality. Cromby’s career is on a steep upward trajectory, the Irish DJ and producer who now calls Berlin home, has played at major clubs and festivals all over the world including esteemed venues like Robert Johnson, The Warehouse Project, Fabric & Boiler Room. Becoming a regular at Panorama Bar, Cromby was invited to do the infamous closing slot which he did with an immense 11 hour set back in December 2019, returning again this year for more. 

Cutting his teeth holding down a six year residency at the legendary Shine in Belfast, Crombys first record came out in 2012 on New Yorks The Love Revolution. Then came two releases on Berlins Tenderpark and a relocation to Berlin via London. 

2018 and 2019 proved to be breakthrough years in his career, seeing him release on three groundbreaking labels; Sulta Selects Silver Service, Feel My Bicep & Unknown To The Unknown.

2020 is set to be even bigger with Cromby embarking on tours of Australia, Asia and the Americas. With two more EPs already signed to respected labels, its more than safe to say he is one to watch.

Welcome to APP, "the one-man-label", home for the many monikers and productions of Silviu Costinescu, best known as Alien Pimp in the music world. International creative powerhouse, active in most things art / media , particularly known as a Bass Music OG, founder of DubKraft Records and several other labels, creator of the seminal album series "Eastern Sound Architects" and "Cinematic Dubstep / D&B / Bass Music", artist, DJ, producer, writer, videographer, jack of all trades in arts and media.  	

For bookings / rmxs / videos / other inquiries: alienpimp2003 at yahoo dot com

At the age of 7, Silviu Costinescu, the real name behind Alien Pimp and SubJazz, was living in the slums of Bucharest, Romania, playing football during the day and reading Jules Verne during the night.
At the age of 14, he was still living in the slums, but having his own show of alternative music on one of the first private radio stations in Bucharest, Radio Nova 22.
At the age of 20, he was awarded First Prize @ Assos Music New Talent Festival and started to get wide recognition as a local producer and performer.
At the age of 27. New York Times was seeing him as one of the main figures of the new Romanian music scene, had his face shown on CNN for pioneering Internet as a medium for artistic collaborations, he was long after 100 stage performances. He was also writing for several magazines and newspapers, most notably the Romanian Playboy and Popcorn. Also did a crazy Tarantinesque photo-shooting for FHM as a fashion model.
At the age of 35 he was a prominent name in the trenches of bass music in Barcelona, Spain, as a DJ, producer and promoter, after having toured half Europe.
Nowadays, in his early 40's, he started to discover Africa, taking a temporary break from the stages, but very active in the studio and on Internet, involved in many music projects, running a few record labels, managing bands and directing music videos.

Media: BBC, MIxmag, MTV, CNN, New York Times, Knowledge Mag, Ministry of Sound, Ibiza Global Radio, Bravo, Popcorn, AtomicTV, SubFM, Resident Mag, DubstepFM, KaneFM, Radio Free Europe, InMadrid, Radio France International, and 100+ more radio stations and magazines.

Clubs played: Flex (Vienna), Razzmatazz (Barcelona), BeCool (Barcelona), Studio Martin (Bucharest), Twist Club (Madrid), BlackBox (Sofia), Fabrica (Bucharest) and 100+ more locations and festivals

Simone was born in Genoa, Italy in 1980.
Since he was a kid, he has always been surrounded by music.
He started with classical music, playing piano. Then he discovered a new world of music, with different sounds, so far away from what he was used to listen to.
He has been deeply fascinated by these new musical scenes, and in the late 90s he started to get involved in jazz, funk and electro music.
He got more and more involved in electro music, listening to the sounds from Detroit, Frankfurt, London, Sweden and Naples.

His style is in constant evolution, a mix of tribal and funk sounds, deep bassline and hypnotic grooves.

Robert Babicz has been redefining the boundaries of electronic music since the early 1990s. His unique artistry encompasses sound, vision, emotion and spirituality. sOMbOM (a brief history)

sOMbOM is a club friendly, electronic music, digital only label and was conceived by Acid Casuals in early 2009.

In 2006, Acid Casuals embark on the launch of their club night sOMbOM in Cardiff, leading to an end of year party with Claude VonStroke. They also start their two year long monthly residency at BBC Radio Wales where as well as their choice flavours of techno and house music, they featured label nights, the likes of which included Raum, Pokerflat, Connaisseur, Minus, Kaliber, Made to Play etc.

2007 sees sOMbOM's first Birthday party at Cardiff’s infamous Coal exchange with Green Velvet, Alex Smoke and Jamie Jones making up the line up. sOMbOM continues to organise events throughout the year bringing together SFA and Weatherall for a party at London's Corsica Studios as part of their U.K tour.

In 2008, sOMbOM continues to bring guests to Cardiff including the likes of Craig Richards, Agoria, Silicone Soul, etc. As well as Acid Casuals’ residency at London’s Corsica studios, with plays along side Daniel Bell, Phonique, Derrick Carter, Matthias Tanzmann, Octave One and more before taking time out to write new material for Acid Casuals.

Following (successful) releases in the past with NOVAMUTE and BELOW, 2009 saw the latest Casuals compositions released on their newly conceived sOMbOM label, to be hosted, featured and promoted on sOMbOM.eu. Here you will also find a new 24hr radio channel and a 'gratis' page, where you can exclusively download free tracks, soundscapes ,DJ tools’ and visual art.

I don't want to write in the third person. I don't have the self confidence to something like that. So I'll give it to you straight, right from the source: My name is Jamison, but some of my friends like to call me The Tremulance. As The Tremulance, I like to make electronic songs; some are meant to make you dance, but some are meant to make you feel a little sleepy. I started making these songs my second year of college. I can still remember inviting Graeme down to my room (he lived two floors above me) to "listen to my new beats". I remember him enjoying them, but I doubt they were all that good. That's just how nice of a guy he was, and probably still is. In the last few years, I've started singing over the beats, in an attempt to convey some sort of gradiose, Bob Dylan-esque message about the probelms with our society. Well, not actually. Most of the time, the lyrics are about dancing, or girls. What can I say, I know my craft. That being said, there are more important things to me than just dancing and girls, and there are some songs on the new record that showcase that. Oh yes, the new record. It's called "Polaroids". It's sort of collection of moments over the last couple of years, like a shoebox of old polaroids. There are songs about good nights spent dancing with friends, heartbreak, missing loved ones, missing the ocean, and the now infamous 'Dance Trap', which actually occurred. We'll go for coffee sometime, and I'll tell you all about it. Until then, I hope that this record has something you can resonate with, and that it will be a record that grows on you over time. Those are always the best ones.

THE LIFERS/NONION BREED are Marios & Paschalis Chatzigeorgiou, they were born together in an era when music was all about feel.

As twins they did all the same things at the same time, one of which was to embrace their parents music culture (60's to 80's), which included soul, disco, pop, rock and classical. The 90's gave them many more influences, from house to mellow techno with their elder brother, a DJ, contributing to their development as musicians and producers.

THE LIFERS/NONION BREED have a music education garnered from their passion for music. They play keyboards and percussion and have studied the science of electronics to give them the knowledge and familiarity of analogue and digital technology together with the methods of synthesis to produce the sounds they need.

THE LIFERS/NONION BREED have a constant appetite to make music, from French feel house with big basslines and disco cuts through to powerpop and electro-­‐disco, and all with atmospheric vibes.

Marios & Paschalis want to make people feel good; “We give our best, so let the music do the rest.”

Born in Washington D.C. and raised in Cologne Henri Kohn was educated in his early years by his fathers extensive collection of jazz and quality black music. After been revolutionized by rap music and taking part in breakdancing competitions in his youth Henri was kissed by the beauty of house, taping music from the radio.

By the age of 15, he sneaked himself into the Cologne nightlife dancing the night away in dark and sweaty clubs and by the age of 17, he landed his first residencies at various clubs in Cologne, playing Chicago and Detroit influenced sound.

Since then Henri has become a pillar of the house scene in Germany, with residencies at most of the top clubs in the area and other German cities, as well as successful spots on the Balearic Islands.
Henri has taken the step up to the international DJ circuit in the last few years and has played all over Germany, in the U.S, France, Spain, Greece, Russia, Switzerland, Poland, Italy and the U.K.

To him House Music is a Healer that brings people from all cultural backgrounds together on the same dancefloor to have a good time. Henri Kohn is known to bring people in the Zone with his skills of reading the crowd and picking the right record at the right time.

No matter if bigroom, frontroom, backroom, terrace or the beach, he loves preaching his vision of house to any crowd, thanks to a wide horizon and taste of electronic music to choose from.

With extensive radio experience and his current position as A&R at Clubstar & Conya Records and Press and P&R Head Honcho of Soulstar, Little Angel & Lola´s World, Henri continues to be an in-demand DJ who describes his style as HOUSE MUSIC FOR GROWNUPS...tribal-, techy-, deep-, jazzy-, afro-, vocal-, electro-, oldskool-, broken-beat, straight-beat, offbeat...unbeatable high quality music...whatever...as long as it got soul !

Honey Dijon had carved a distinct niche for herself in the world of underground electronic music, coming to be associated with exquisitely curated cross-genre sets and total dance-floor chaos wherever she plays - from Berghain to Space or Smart Bar. As a producer, her reputation for bringing this knowledge to her forward thinking creations is growing all the time. 

Born and raised in Chicago - the home of house music - the city's influence on Honey’s style is deeply ingrained. Like many in the scene, her love affair with music began upon hearing her parent’s soul and R&B records at home. Soon, it was clear to her that she needed to be the one dropping the needle on the record at her parent’s basement parties - at which point there was no turning back - club life beckoned.
Before long she was obsessively collecting tracks from hallowed stores like Imports Etc and Gramaphone in Chicago - developing the taste and style that would become her own. Through digging at these legendary stores, Honey met and formed a long lasting friendship with Derrick Carter, who became a mentor. It was he who introduced her to the underground of Chicago where she was exposed to the sounds of jacking house and Detroit techno. After relocating to New York City, Honey also met another music giant Danny Tenaglia, whose legendary sets at Twilo were also a major source of inspiration. “Danny heavily influenced my sound as a DJ’, says Honey. “The drama of his delivery and risk taking always informed me of how I wanted to present music. Of course, Derrick and Chicago house were also very influential in my development as an artist, so it’s this combination of Chicago and New York that has helped me develop my signature sound.”

This signature sound can be heard all over her much lauded mixes for various online platforms like Resident Advisor, yet it’s in the flesh where her power is really revealed. Her blending of the bump of Chicago with more classic New York sounds and various European influences (Honey splits her time between New York and Berlin), her sets are known for their strong programming, passion and integrity. 

The art of the mix itself is also very important to Honey as anyone who has witnessed her play can testify - her subtle mixing skills and the deft, almost sensuous transitions between house and techno deliver a warm, hypnotic vibe within her sets. She has brought her talents to many of the best venues around the world - from Panorama Bar in Berlin, Sub Club in Glasgow, The Block in Tel Aviv, Output in NYC, Space in Ibiza and of course Smart Bar in Chicago - the list goes on, and her influence grows every show. 
In the studio, Honey brings a unique perspective and experience to her productions. Unsurprisingly, the influences of such an illustrious background run deep, but do not overwhelm her forward-looking works. This is instantly clear from her releases and remixes on Classic Records, particularly with the recent collaborations with Seven Davis Jr and Tim K and the upcoming album on the same label due in summer 2017. 

Honey has also been highly active at the intersection of fashion and music, compiling and curating the music for Louis Vuitton’s men’s shows, while also working closely with British designer Kim Jones. Honey has featured in style bible The Gentlewoman as well as being profiled in the New York Times Style section in 2013. 

 An in-demand speaker and contributor on issues surrounding gender in club culture, Honey has also appeared on high profile platforms such as Red Bull Music’ Fireside Chat and Kindness Radio show. In February 2017 she will feature in a panel discussion at MoMa's PS1 alongside Genesis P Porridge of Throbbing Gristle and DJ Sprinkles discussing Gender and Electronic Music. Honey will also be performing at BPM Festival, Coachella, and Movement and other high profile events around the globe.

As a child, Matty Harris aka The Narcoleptic, developed a keen sense for music. At the ripe age of 10, he acquired a cassette recorder. This cassette recorder was the focal point of his entire lively hood at this point in time. He had the ability to record all of his favorite songs on the radio. He would dissect and examine each song in order to understand why it made him feel they way he felt. He listened to everything from Classic Rock to Soul Music. While visiting his cousins, who lived on the south side of Chicago, he was introduced to House Music. A local college radio station hosted a show dedicated to this raw, new sound forged in the streets of Chicago. The radio host was T Chablis. Matty could never tune in to his show from the suburbs, so every time he visited his cousins he would make it a priority to listen to the show and record it. He was enamored by this music. His eagerness to learn more stoked his internal flame of curiosity.

After poking around his cousins crew, he stumbled upon a fellow who had some House Music records which he had no interest. Two copies of "Come to me" -Gwendolyn, "You Ain't Really Down- Status IV, "Girls Girls"- Solo and "Funk You Up"- Jesse Saunders. Not long after, Matty was playing records in his bedroom every day. It was 1986, and House Music was taking control. It wasn't until he moved from the suburbs to the city of Chicago in the early 90's that he found his true calling in the underground scene. Finally, after a lot of hard work and dedication, he earned himself a residency at smart bar's Tuesday night romp,"Pump",where his dear friends Derrick Carter, Miles Maeda and Terry Martin also played host to many up and coming All stars. When"Pump" came to a conclusion, Matty became a part of The thriving urban club scene. With residencies all over the city of Chicago, playing with top players such as Derrick Carter, D.J. Sneak , Mark Farina, Diz, and the list continues.

Currently, Matty's commitments are to his studio and regular weekly gigs throughout Chicago. He has released compositions as The Narcoleptic on Classic Music Co., Kwench, Jump Recordings, Get Up Recordings, Green House, Planet Scratch,  Loveslap and Leftroom . Not to mention a few remixes for Savvy Recordings, Beatbums and Plant Scratch.

Conscious Slide, or Paul Lau as he is known to his friends and family, is a man born out of time, waiting for his moment.
46 years old with 24 years of clubbing under his belt, he’s seen a lot: having experienced the vibe from many a DJ at clubs and festivals across the world, he’s learnt from the best and seen first-hand what can make or break a dance floor.
Starting his journey into DJing on vinyl, he spent the next few years practicing and learning, which lead him down a Progressive House route for a number of years and which, though he enjoyed this at the time, resulted in his struggle to find his own unique sound in an over-saturated market and one that began to feel stale to him. Rather than getting disheartened and giving up this only inspired him to try harder, with him acknowledging and accepting his deepening yearn for an edgier sound, which is when techno saved his life. Stepping out of the confines of his beloved vinyl and with the ever-expanding new digital frontier provided by the now-accessible internet, he was able to step in to a whole new world of music. And with each new track found, which opened the doors to new artists, new DJs and new labels, things became exciting again.
Skip forward to today and he continues to immerse himself on dance floors both in the UK and internationally, and which provide the impetus for his own DJ sets. Now rocking a full digital set up with Traktor at its heart, 4 deck mixing, running through a Play Differently Model One mixer, he feels alive and he is ready to be heard.

Among my earliest memories are crawling under the piano while Mom played. I took piano lessons as a child like most people did, but gave it up after 5 years to continue with violin in fourth grade.
A veteran of school orchestras for 20 years, I first began to flex my own creative (musical) impulses in the late 1980's by improvising on the keyboard part from "San Jacinto" on "Peter Gabriel Plays Live," the first cassette (and non-classical recording) I ever bought in 1983. 

After moving to Chicago in 2001, bored with work, and not finding an ensemble I liked, I started improvising more on violin in a mostly empty apartment with plenty of hard surfaces. Things began getting more interesting when I added an electric pickup, guitar pedals (I swear I didn't hear Andrew Bird until several years after, and line-in to the laptop. 
As part of Twelve Modern, an improv quintet (guitar, bass, violin, drums, percussion, I finally got to... um... rock. I also learned to truly listen to others in a musical setting. Twelve Modern (https://twelvemodern.bandcamp.com/) released one album, Like Ghosts, and recorded additional material between 2004-2009 that - I promise - is really great!

In 2008, I took composition classes at Access Contemporary Ensemble. Other than that, I mostly find my way around things and go by intuition.

It's been a while since I've posted, but since then I was given a guitar (thanks, Emily!), lived and worked in Haiti for 3 years, and went to grad school. Here I am, back in 2016 with a few new things.

Hope you'll enjoy. Please feel free to comment!

Right place, right time. It's an old cliché, but it's one that's been the definition of Dennis Ferrer's musical career. Just as the dance music world was heading into the world of afro-centric house, Ferrer was there. And then, when it began to embrace the mix of tech and soul, Ferrer was there again, leading the way with his impeccable productions. As Ferrer goes, it seems, so does electronic music. And, as someone who's never content to do the same thing twice, it's clear that he'll be staying on top for years to come.

Ferrer burst back into the consciousness of most dance music heads with the release of "Sandcastles," (Ibadan) his collaboration with Jerome Sydenham in 2003. But, to his credit, Ferrer didn't simply repeat the formula afterwards. He has continued to push a variety of genres all at once. It's clear that Ferrer isn't content to rest on his laurels: he's too busy dreaming up new ways to shock and delight audiences.

In the mid-90’s, Ferrer was crafting techno records as Morph and then had success in the Afro and gospel house scenes with releases via his Sfere label, an imprint he began alongside Kerri Chandler. But it's this past work that gives his new productions such resonance: unlike many of this house peers, Ferrer's techno experience has given him an edge that you can hear in his recent work.

"Son of Raw," (Ibadan) "Church Lady," (Defected) "Underground Is My Home," (King Street Sounds), "Touched the Sky" (King Street Sounds), “Transitions” (King Street Sounds), “P 2 Da J” (Defected),  “Sinfonia Della Notte” (Strictly Rhythm), “Hey Hey” (Objektivity), “Red Room” (Objektivity), “Underground” Nick Curly – Dennis Ferrer Remix (Defected), to name a few, have all been huge dance floor anthems and all show a different side of the Ferrer personality as well as his impressive range as producer and remixer.

Ferrer has brought his ‘anything goes’ approach to his label, Objektivity.  Celebrating its 8th anniversary in 2014, the imprint has thus far focused itself on vocals, featuring often unlikely turns from indie heroes like Ane Brun and Télépopmusik. Low slung and deep, Objektivity is a cutting-edge label in touch with its time, putting a uniquely American spin on the deep house revival that is currently making waves in Europe. Objektivity is a living, breathing thing - one that's set to drop bombs on the dance floor for years to come.

While Ferrer closes out 2013 with “Mind Ur Step” (Defected), “Mind Ur Dub” (Objektivity) and a remix of Coyu - “Salvation” (Noir Music), the best is yet to come. With a deep knowledge of the past and a constant push for the future, Ferrer remains one of the true greats of house music - a leader and innovator whose enjoying the buzz around him but keeping on pushing the limits. Stay tuned.

Aaron Ross is a name synonymous with quality House music around the globe. His career in music spans over 15 years, Having held the position of  A&R manager for Defected Records for 6 years, and previously holding the only house show  BBC 1xtra for 5 years and earlier in his career handling club promotions and dance music A&R for Virgin Records UK.

From his roots in pirate radio, to playing alongside and remixing dance music’s biggest names Aaron is
renowned for his inimitable take on House music, drawing inspiration from the old skool and fusing it with contemporary, innovative sounds to make his DJing style unique and fresh. 

His passion for house music in the 90’s quickly took him to a long term residency at institutional London club night, Missdemeanours, playing alongside the likes of house music heroes Lottie, Danny Rampling, David Morales and Erick Morillo.

His first track under the guise of Rain People and featuring Marcus Begg, was released on Osiris music in 2003 and became something of a soulful anthem subsequently picked up by U.S label soulshine, that release was quickly followed with a string of solid productions including acclaimed releases under the alias Fanatix alongside Neil Pierce.  To date he holds an extensive list of successful self produced tracks and has acquired the reputation of a sought-after remixer for artists such as Jamiroquai, Blaze, Ultra Nate, Kings of Tomorrow, Dennis Ferrer, Ben Westbeach and Estelle.

His production style is instantly recognisable with a strong mix sound, timeless songs and solid drums, and in 2008 released, to critical acclaim, a full length LP on BBE Records under the Fanatix alias. Other recent projects include 2 releases for restless soul , the follow up to “Love Potion” with Gia Mellish entitled “Feel My Love”  and an EP of Deep house cuts on acclaimed label Lost My Dog also forthcoming in September 2013 is a single for the legendary King St Sounds label featuring the vocal talents of April Morgan titled “No More Lies”

Aaron has also recently formed his own artist management company Infinite Future Management where his years of experience will see him guide the careers of others to reach the heights of global success.

Rob Paine's roots run deep. From the moment he heard the deep dubby sounds of Reggae as just a youth he knew he had found his sound. His love for the heavy Reggae sounds grew into a forward movement and soon took on a life of it's own by using the foundation of reggae music as his center piece for all his house & deep techno productions. In 1993 Rob began DJ'ing and throwing events with his crew, "Circle Productions", who were responsible for the most popular parties and weekly club nights in Philadelphia throughout the 90's. During this time Rob started producing a broad range of reggae and reggae influenced music including house, deep techno, broken beat, dub, and down-tempo. His unique sounds were soon being released on labels like Large, Tango, Shaboom & Greyhound just to name a few. Following the success of those tracks, his music was licensed to labels like Bedrock, Fabric & NRK. In 1998 Rob formed his own world-renowned imprint, Worship Recordings. 

The Shakedown events were soon developed as an outlet to showcase his productions and the artists signed to his label. Twelve years later, the Shakedown is still going strong.

Over the years Rob has performed at some of the most exclusive clubs and events in locations like Canada, Mexico, Jamaica and London. He has played the infamous Fabric, PS1 in NYC, and Francois K's Deep Space event. He has held monthly residencies in San Francisco, weeklies in South Beach Miami, performed year after year at the Shambhala & Soundwave festivals in BC, and is currently holding down residencies in DC and Philadelphia. When we asked Rob about holding it altogether he said "It's really exciting to be able to switch between the two genres of house & reggae... always keeping a fresh perspective on both genres and pushing the limits with new sound elements."

Rob produces the majority of the projects released on Worship. In 1999 he was awarded the 'Most Innovative Producer' by the Philadelphia City Paper. His 'dub house' style of production marked him as a forward thinker, blazing the path for future infusions of dub and house sounds for years to come.

He recently released 'What You See' EP on Matt Tolfrey's LeftRoom Records under the name Circle with partner Keith Landis & Gerhardt Koerner (Rise 8) that is doing extremely well. Being selected by Maceo Plex for recent mix compilation. Circle also released the Dark Waves EP on Worship in January, 2014. And a 45 for the vinyl only dub label ZamZam Sounds with his bredren Ras Heights under the name Heights + Worship. You will see a lot more releases from Circle and Rob Paine's other projects including a full length Rise 8 album and a EP on i Records.

Rob Paine is an innovator, visionary & one of the cities most prolific DJ's, producers & musicians. He continually pushes the elements of dub into house and techno music. He has created a world renowned studio & sound system with his full commitment to the city of Philadelphia's ever continuing music mecca. His talent shines furiously every time he performs whether it is House or Reggae or somewhere in between. Rob Paine does not disappoint. Pure quality every time.

Martinesque started his nighttime adventures with tasteful house records towards the tail end of the nineties. Inspired by the deep explorations of Chicago and New York stalwarts, he’s found pleasure in playing out low-slung grooves and stripped-back entries from all corners of electronic music. Since, the Basel native has honed his craft in clubs around the country and beyond. Methodically stitching together records from his vaults, Martinesque escalates from meditative rhythm workouts to subdued dancefloor drama in a controlled fashion. He’s developed his artistic vision through residencies in some of Switzerland’s most cherished spaces, but nowadays found his spot as Elysia’s head of bookings, where he’s since showcased a full-spectrum analysis of contemporary dance music. His most recent endeavour is Adam’s Bite, a cross-disciplinary cooperation zoning in on oblique music and visual arts, further cementing his position as a driving figure in a thriving scene.
